explanation:
TKIP happens to be an interim solution to overcome some security shortcomings with early 802.11 security protocols, specifically with WEP. With the passage of time and development of newer standards, TKIP should no longer be used and is in fact deprecated (removed) from the 802.11 standard. The other answers describe different features of current 802.11 security features. For reference:

-&nbsp;TKIP: Temporary Key Integrity Protocol.

-&nbsp;CCMP: Counter CBC-MAC Protocol.&nbsp;

-&nbsp;GCMP: Galois Counter Mode Protocol.&nbsp;

-&nbsp;AES: Advanced Encryption Standard.

Of the four answers, only the correct answers shows syntax that IOS would accept as correct. The incorrect answers include mistakes such as:&nbsp;


	Using the ip keyword with a standard ACL
	Placing the permit keyword before the ACL number (10)

The show ip interfaces command output from IOS XE lists four lines about enabled interface ACLs. Two lines describe ACLs for the outbound direction and two lines for the inbound direction. For each pair of output lines, one lists the common ACL while&nbsp;the other lists the regular ACL.&nbsp;

If the configuration uses the ip access-group common&hellip; in command, it defines two ACLs in the same direction: A common ACL and a regular ACL. The show ip interface command output lists those two ACLs on separate consecutive lines, identifying the common ACL on the line with the text shown in the question stem.

Alternately, suppose the configuration uses the ip access-group&hellip; in interface subcommand without the common keyword. In that case, it defines a normal ACL for that direction &ndash; and informs the router not to use a common ACL. In that case, the show command output lists the same line of output, but with a value for the Common ACL of&nbsp;&ldquo;not set.&rdquo;

This question shows four consecutive ip access-group interface subcommands for the same interface and the same inbound direction. Repeating an ip access-group command under the same interface for the same direction replaces any previous command for that same direction. So, the router accepts each command in succession, but it replaces the previous one. In effect, only the final ip access-group command remains in the configuration in this case. That command does not use the common keyword, so the interface does not use a common ACL in the inbound direction. The command output will list &ldquo;not set&rdquo;.

First, note that the question tells us the commands exist in a text editor and are pasted into configuration mode. That sequence means that the commands, as shown, may be incorrect and be rejected by IOS outright. However, all four ip&nbsp;access-group interface subcommands have the correct syntax.

The four syntactically correct consecutive ip access-group interface subcommands reside under the same interface and refer to the same inbound direction. Repeating an ip access-group command under the same interface for the same direction replaces any previous command for that same direction. So, the router accepts each command in succession, but it replaces the previous one. Only the final ip access-group command shown in this question&nbsp;remains in the configuration by the end of the configuration process. That command sets the common ACL to the ACL named &quot;four,&quot; which is the correct answer.

The show ip interfaces command output from IOS XE lists four lines about enabled interface ACLs. If the configuration uses the ip access-group common&hellip; in command, it defines two ACLs in the same direction: A common ACL and a regular ACL. The show ip interface command output lists those two ACLs on separate consecutive lines. The line that begins &quot;IP Common access list is&quot; ends with the name or number of the enabled common ACL, in this case, &quot;four.&quot;&nbsp;

When the enable secret command uses type 9 encoding, due to keyword scrypt, it uses the scrypt hash algorithm.&nbsp;

When the enable secret command uses type 8 encoding, due to keyword SHA-256, it uses the SHA0256 hash algorithm, which includes an algorithm called PBKDF2.&nbsp;

When the enable secret password has an encoding type of 5, it is leveraging MD5 as the hashing algorithm, which is the default algorithm for this command. The specific command is enable [algorithm-type md5] secret password.

The enable secret command does not store the password in clear text.
